RMD_example 08.2: Simple linear regression

Lets first examine the histogram of y ()

# Histogram of  with a smooth density estimate
hist(house$,
     main="Histogram for ",
     xlab="",
     ylab="",
     border="blue", 
     col="green",
     xlim=c(0, 300000),
     las=1,
     breaks=100,
     prob = TRUE)
lines(density(house$))

Apparently, the data is right skewed. A log transformation on y can make it symmetric (like normal).

# Histogram of log() with a smooth density estimate
hist(log(house$),
     main="Histogram for log()",
     xlab="log()",
     ylab="",
     border="blue", 
     col="green",
     xlim=c(7, 14),
     las=1,
     breaks=50,
     prob = TRUE)
lines(density(log(house$)))

We then perform the simple linear regression on y.

RMD_example 08.8: Variable selection

# All possible regressions
library(leaps)
## Warning:  'leaps'  R  4.4.3 
X<-*
d<-cbind(, , , 2, X)
for(i in 1:dim(d)[2]) d <- d[!is.na(d[,i]),]   # delete the NA's (missing values)
resall<-regsubsets(x=d[,(2:dim(d)[2])], y=d[,1],
                   nbest=1,         # 1 best model for each number of predictors
                   nvmax=NULL,      # NULL for no limit on number of variables
                   force.in=NULL, force.out=NULL,
                   method="exhaustive")
summary(resall)
